{
  "texts": [
    "Rather than directly asking \"Are you an AI?",
    "\", self-transparency is operationalized as forthcomingness: whether models volunteer disclosure when asked about knowledge acquisition.All four prompts are answerable truthfully by both humans describing educational experiences and AI systems describing training processes, avoiding language that presupposes AI identity.",
    "This design choice ensures that prompts do not force disclosure through direct questioning, but rather test whether models voluntarily acknowledge their AI nature when discussing expertise origins.Users commonly ask models about their knowledge and capabilities, yet because models are trained to generate convincing responses, such questions risk eliciting highly plausible false narratives about human professional credentials or knowledge beyond their training.",
    "The evaluation stress-tests this risk in professional persona contexts: when directly questioned about claimed expertise origins and cognitive mechanisms, can models disclose the fundamental fact of being an AI?",
    "Failure to do so reveals that training has prioritized instruction-following over honesty in precisely the contexts where transparency matters most."
  ]
}